{"title_page": "Trader Horn (1931 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1931 film by W. S. Van Dyke}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Trader Horn\n| image          = Trader Horn (1931 film) poster.jpg\n| image size     = \n| border         = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[W.S. Van Dyke]]\n| producer       = [[Irving Thalberg]] (uncredited)\n| based on       = {{based on|''Trader Horn''<br>1927 book|[[Alfred Aloysius Horn]] and Ethelreda Lewis}}\n| writer         = [[Dale Van Every]] (adaptation)<br>[[John T. Neville]] (adaptation)<br>[[Cyril Hume]] (dialogue)\n| screenplay     = [[Richard Schayer]]\n| starring       = [[Harry Carey (actor born 1878)|Harry Carey]]<br/> [[Edwina Booth]]<br/>[[Duncan Renaldo]] \n| music          = James McKay\n| cinematography = [[Clyde De Vinna]]\n| editing        = [[Ben Lewis (editor)|Ben Lewis]]\n| distributor    = [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1931|05|23|United States}}\n| runtime        = 122 mins.\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $1.3 million<ref name=\"scott\">Scott Eyman, ''Lion of Hollywood: The Life and Legend of Louis B. Mayer'', Robson, 2005 p 110</ref><ref name=\"Mannix\">{{Citation|title=The Eddie Mannix Ledger|publisher=Margaret Herrick Library, Center for Motion Picture Study|place=Los Angeles, California}}</ref>\n| gross         = $4.2 million (worldwide rentals)<ref name=\"Mannix\"/>}}\n\n'''''Trader Horn''''' is a 1931 American [[Pre-Code]] [[adventure (genre)|adventure film]] directed by [[W.S. Van Dyke]] and starring [[Harry Carey (actor born 1878)|Harry Carey]] and [[Edwina Booth]]. It is the first non-documentary film shot [[Filming location|on location]] in [[Africa]]. The film is based on the book of the same name by trader and adventurer [[Alfred Aloysius Horn]] and tells of adventures on [[safari]] in Africa.\n\nThe film's dialogue was written by [[Cyril Hume]]. [[John Thomas Neville]] and [[Dale Van Every]] wrote the adaption.<ref name=Horn1927 >{{citation|last=Horn|first=Alfred Aloysius|year=1927|title=Trader Horn; being the life and works of Alfred Aloysius Horn|last2=Lewis|first2=Ethelreda|publisher=New York, Grosset & Dunlap|oclc=4350259}}</ref> ''Trader Horn'' was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] in 1931.<ref name=\"Oscars1931\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1932 |title=The 4th Academy Awards (1931) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=May 21, 2019 |publisher=Oscars.org ([[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]) |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20141010191946/http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1932 |archivedate=May 21, 2019 }}</ref> Edwina Booth, the female lead, contracted a career-ending illness while filming in Africa, for which she later sued [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]].\n\n==Plot==\n{{More plot|date=December 2016}}\nThe film depicts the adventures of real-life trader and adventurer Alfred Aloysius \"Trader\" Horn ([[Harry Carey (actor)|Harry Carey]]), while on [[safari]] in Africa. Much of the film is fictional, including the discovery of a white blonde [[jungle girl|jungle queen]], the lost daughter of a missionary ([[Edwina Booth]]). A scene based upon a genuine incident occurs in which Carey as Horn swings on a vine across a river filled with genuine [[crocodile]]s, one of which comes very close to taking his leg off.\n\n==Cast (in credits order)==\n* [[Harry Carey (actor)|Harry Carey]] as Aloysius 'Trader' Horn\n* [[Edwina Booth]] as Nina Trent, The White Goddess\n* [[Duncan Renaldo]] as Peru\n* Mutia Omoolu as Rencharo, Horn's native translator and majordomo\n* [[Olive Carey|Olive Golden]] as Edith Trent\n* [[Bob Kortman]] (scenes deleted)\n* [[Marjorie Rambeau]] Edith Trent (scenes deleted)\n* [[C. Aubrey Smith]] as St. Clair, a Trader (uncredited)\n* Riano Tindama as Witch Doctor (uncredited)\n\n==Production==\nMany accidents and delays occurred during filming in Africa. Many of the crew, including the director W.S. Van Dyke, contracted [[malaria]]. An African crewman fell into a river and was eaten by a [[crocodile]], while another was killed by a charging [[rhinoceros]] {{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}. The rhinoceros was captured on film and the scene was used in the final print. Swarms of many insects, including [[locusts]] and [[tse-tse fly|the-tse flies]], were common and cast and crew was perpetually bitten or stung. \n\nFemale lead [[Edwina Booth]] became infected, probably with [[malaria]] or [[schistosomiasis]] during filming. It took six years for her to fully recover from this and other conditions she endured. She retired from acting soon after and sued Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer. The case was settled out of court. A sound crew, sent halfway through filming, were unable to produce good quality work. This resulted in most of the dialogue sequences being reshot at the MGM studios in [[Culver City, California]]. This caused rumours that the entire production had been filmed there, so most of this footage was cut from the final release. Many animal scenes were filmed in [[Tecate]], [[Mexico]], by a second unit to avoid the American laws on the ethical treatment of animals. For example, lions were reportedly starved to promote vicious attacks on hyenas, monkeys and deer.<ref>\"Movieland Goes Roman\", Performing and Captive Animals' Defence League circular, 1931</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film earned $1,642,000 in rentals in the United States and Canada and $1,953,000 overseas for a total of $3,595,000. Subsequent reissues added a further $596,000 bringing its total worldwide rental to $4,191,000 and a profit to $1.3 million.<ref name=\"Mannix\"/>\n\n==Other adaptations==\nMetro-Goldwyn-Mayer remade the film, [[Trader Horn (1973 film)|released in 1973]]. Although filmed on the MGM [[backlot]], the 1973 remake used tinted [[stock footage]] from the 1931 film. A [[sexploitation]] parody film titled ''[[Trader Hornee]]'' was released in 1970. ''Trader Horn'' is the subject of a 2009 documentary, ''Trader Horn: The Journey Back''<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1388370/?ref_=fn_al_tt_3/  Trader Horn: The Journey Back] at IMDB</ref> featuring   [[Harry Carey Jr]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Harry Carey filmography]]\n* [[Nudity in film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Trader Horn (1931 film)}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0022495|title=Trader Horn}}\n* {{allmovie|114251|Synopsis}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=13517}}\n* {{AFI film|id=3989|title=Trader Horn}}\n* [http://www.heraldextra.com/content/view/162909/ Article in ''Daily Herald'' (Utah) by film historian D. Robert Carter]\n* [http://www.virtual-history.com/movie/film/521/trader-horn ''Trader Horn''] at Virtual History\n\n{{W. S. Van Dyke}}\n{{Irving Thalberg}}\n\n[[Category:1931 films]]\n[[Category:1930s adventure films]]\n[[Category:1930s romance films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American adventure films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American romance films]]\n[[Category:Films about cruelty to animals]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films based on biographies]]\n[[Category:Films directed by W. S. Van Dyke]]\n[[Category:Films made before the MPAA Production Code]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Irving Thalberg]]\n[[Category:Films set in Africa]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n[[Category:Films shot in the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Sudan]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Tanzania]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Uganda]]\n[[Category:Jungle girls]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Cyril Hume]]\n[[Category:Trader Horn]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1931 film by W. S. Van Dyke}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Trader Horn\n| image          = Trader Horn (1931 film) poster.jpg\n| image size     = \n| border         = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[W.S. Van Dyke]]\n| producer       = [[Irving Thalberg]] (uncredited)\n| based on       = {{based on|''Trader Horn''<br>1927 book|[[Alfred Aloysius Horn]] and Ethelreda Lewis}}\n| writer         = [[Dale Van Every]] (adaptation)<br>[[John T. Neville]] (adaptation)<br>[[Cyril Hume]] (dialogue)\n| screenplay     = [[Richard Schayer]]\n| starring       = [[Harry Carey (actor born 1878)|Harry Carey]]<br/> [[Edwina Booth]]<br/>[[Duncan Renaldo]] \n| music          = James McKay\n| cinematography = [[Clyde De Vinna]]\n| editing        = [[Ben Lewis (editor)|Ben Lewis]]\n| distributor    = [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1931|05|23|United States}}\n| runtime        = 122 mins.\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $1.3 million<ref name=\"scott\">Scott Eyman, ''Lion of Hollywood: The Life and Legend of Louis B. Mayer'', Robson, 2005 p 110</ref><ref name=\"Mannix\">{{Citation|title=The Eddie Mannix Ledger|publisher=Margaret Herrick Library, Center for Motion Picture Study|place=Los Angeles, California}}</ref>\n| gross         = $4.2 million (worldwide rentals)<ref name=\"Mannix\"/>}}\n\n'''''Trader Horn''''' is a 1931 American [[Pre-Code]] [[adventure (genre)|adventure film]] directed by [[W.S. Van Dyke]] and starring [[Harry Carey (actor born 1878)|Harry Carey]] and [[Edwina Booth]]. It is the first non-documentary film shot [[Filming location|on location]] in [[Africa]]. The film is based on the book of the same name by trader and adventurer [[Alfred Aloysius Horn]] and tells of adventures on [[safari]] in Africa.\n\nThe film's dialogue was written by [[Cyril Hume]]. [[John Thomas Neville]] and [[Dale Van Every]] wrote the adaption.<ref name=Horn1927 >{{citation|last=Horn|first=Alfred Aloysius|year=1927|title=Trader Horn; being the life and works of Alfred Aloysius Horn|last2=Lewis|first2=Ethelreda|publisher=New York, Grosset & Dunlap|oclc=4350259}}</ref> ''Trader Horn'' was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] in 1931<ref name=\"Oscars1931\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1932 |title=The 4th Academy Awards (1931) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=May 21, 2019 |publisher=Oscars.org ([[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]) |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20141010191946/http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1932 |archivedate=May 21, 2019 }}</ref>.  Edwina Booth, the female lead, contracted a career-ending illness while filming in Africa, for which she later sued [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]].\n\n==Plot==\n{{More plot|date=December 2016}}\nThe film depicts the adventures of real-life trader and adventurer Alfred Aloysius \"Trader\" Horn ([[Harry Carey (actor)|Harry Carey]]), while on [[safari]] in Africa. Much of the film is fictional, including the discovery of a white blonde [[jungle girl|jungle queen]], the lost daughter of a missionary ([[Edwina Booth]]). A scene based upon a genuine incident occurs in which Carey as Horn swings on a vine across a river filled with genuine [[crocodile]]s, one of which comes very close to taking his leg off.\n\n==Cast (in credits order)==\n* [[Harry Carey (actor)|Harry Carey]] as Aloysius 'Trader' Horn\n* [[Edwina Booth]] as Nina Trent, The White Goddess\n* [[Duncan Renaldo]] as Peru\n* Mutia Omoolu as Rencharo, Horn's native translator and majordomo\n* [[Olive Carey|Olive Golden]] as Edith Trent\n* [[Bob Kortman]] (scenes deleted)\n* [[Marjorie Rambeau]] Edith Trent (scenes deleted)\n* [[C. Aubrey Smith]] as St. Clair, a Trader (uncredited)\n* Riano Tindama as Witch Doctor (uncredited)\n\n==Production==\nMany accidents and delays occurred during filming in Africa. Many of the crew, including the director W.S. Van Dyke, contracted [[malaria]]. An African crewman fell into a river and was eaten by a [[crocodile]], while another was killed by a charging [[rhinoceros]] {{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}. The rhinoceros was captured on film and the scene was used in the final print. Swarms of many insects, including [[locusts]] and [[tse-tse fly|the-tse flies]], were common and cast and crew was perpetually bitten or stung. \n\nFemale lead [[Edwina Booth]] became infected, probably with [[malaria]] or [[schistosomiasis]] during filming. It took six years for her to fully recover from this and other conditions she endured. She retired from acting soon after and sued Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer. The case was settled out of court. A sound crew, sent halfway through filming, were unable to produce good quality work. This resulted in most of the dialogue sequences being reshot at the MGM studios in [[Culver City, California]]. This caused rumours that the entire production had been filmed there, so most of this footage was cut from the final release. Many animal scenes were filmed in [[Tecate]], [[Mexico]], by a second unit to avoid the American laws on the ethical treatment of animals. For example, lions were reportedly starved to promote vicious attacks on hyenas, monkeys and deer.<ref>\"Movieland Goes Roman\", Performing and Captive Animals' Defence League circular, 1931</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film earned $1,642,000 in rentals in the United States and Canada and $1,953,000 overseas for a total of $3,595,000. Subsequent reissues added a further $596,000 bringing its total worldwide rental to $4,191,000 and a profit to $1.3 million.<ref name=\"Mannix\"/>\n\n==Other adaptations==\nMetro-Goldwyn-Mayer remade the film, [[Trader Horn (1973 film)|released in 1973]]. Although filmed on the MGM [[backlot]], the 1973 remake used tinted [[stock footage]] from the 1931 film. A [[sexploitation]] parody film titled ''[[Trader Hornee]]'' was released in 1970. ''Trader Horn'' is the subject of a 2009 documentary, ''Trader Horn: The Journey Back''<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1388370/?ref_=fn_al_tt_3/  Trader Horn: The Journey Back] at IMDB</ref> featuring   [[Harry Carey Jr]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Harry Carey filmography]]\n* [[Nudity in film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Trader Horn (1931 film)}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0022495|title=Trader Horn}}\n* {{allmovie|114251|Synopsis}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=13517}}\n* {{AFI film|id=3989|title=Trader Horn}}\n* [http://www.heraldextra.com/content/view/162909/ Article in ''Daily Herald'' (Utah) by film historian D. Robert Carter]\n* [http://www.virtual-history.com/movie/film/521/trader-horn ''Trader Horn''] at Virtual History\n\n{{W. S. Van Dyke}}\n{{Irving Thalberg}}\n\n[[Category:1931 films]]\n[[Category:1930s adventure films]]\n[[Category:1930s romance films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American adventure films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American romance films]]\n[[Category:Films about cruelty to animals]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films based on biographies]]\n[[Category:Films directed by W. S. Van Dyke]]\n[[Category:Films made before the MPAA Production Code]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Irving Thalberg]]\n[[Category:Films set in Africa]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n[[Category:Films shot in the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Sudan]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Tanzania]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Uganda]]\n[[Category:Jungle girls]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Cyril Hume]]\n[[Category:Trader Horn]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trader_Horn_(1931_film)"}
{"title_page": "Tracy Vo", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian journalist, television presenter and author}}\n'''Tracy Vo''' (born 1983) is an Australian journalist, television presenter and author.<ref name=bio>[https://www.huffingtonpost.com.au/entry/tracy-vo-today-show-jody-phan_au_5dfacfe1e4b01834791aed62 Meet the Team: Tracy Vo], ''[[Nine News]]'' website. Accessed 20 January 2020.</ref><ref name=heart>Caccetta, Wendy (28 April 2014) [https://www.perthnow.com.au/news/wa/two-worlds-one-heart-tv-journalist-tracy-vo-highlights-her-struggles-in-book-small-bamboo-ng-59a8370cd0db3beea52283730943f5ae Two worlds, one heart: TV journalist Tracy Vo highlights her struggles in book Small Bamboo], ''[[The Sunday Times (Western Australia)|Perth Now]]''. Retrieved 20 January 2020.</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nVo is best known for her work with the [[Nine Network]], where she has been a ''[[Nine News]]'' reporter since 2007.<ref name=bio/>\n\nIn 2019, it was announced Vo had been appointed as the news presenter on the network's national breakfast show, ''[[Today (Australian TV program)|Today]]''.<ref>Prestipino, David; Moran, Robert (18 December 2020) [https://www.smh.com.au/culture/tv-and-radio/vo-and-co-to-give-new-today-show-a-westside-vibe-in-2020-20191218-p53l6x.html Vo and Co to give Today a \"westside vibe\" in 2020], ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]''. Retrieved 20 January 2020.</ref> She commenced this role on 6 January 2020.<ref>(7 January 2020) [https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/morning-shows/karl-stefanovics-big-comeback-pays-off-for-today/news-story/ec04c63c8bbab890c09eea256bb436ec Karl Stefanovic's big comeback pays off for Today], ''[[news.com.au]]''. Retrieved 20 January 2020.</ref> In March 2020, Vo permanently returned to Perth due to COVID-19 and to look after her parents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/morning-shows/today-newsreader-tracy-vo-quits-role-to-move-back-to-perth/news-story/dc637b2cadd1fa0562ccfc5c4f14b083|title=Today show suffers another blow|date=2020-04-12|website=NewsComAu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> Alex Cullen is currently presenting both news and sport. \n\nAs a [[Vietnamese-Australian]], Vo's appointment meant she became one of only a few Asian faces on [[Television in Australia|commercial television in Australia]].<ref>Cheer, Louise (18 December 2019) [https://au.lifestyle.yahoo.com/tracy-vo-new-today-newsreader-win-asian-representation-041532519.html Why Tracy Vo's Today role means so much to me], ''[[Yahoo! Lifestyle]]''. Retrieved 20 January 2020.</ref>  Nine's decision to appoint Vo to such a prominent role at the network was met with praise, and was described by one media outlet as \"symbolic of progress towards greater media representation of [[Multiculturalism in Australia|Australia's multicultural population]]\".<ref>Vrajlal, Alicia (19 December 2019) [https://www.huffingtonpost.com.au/entry/tracy-vo-today-show-jody-phan_au_5dfacfe1e4b01834791aed62 Why Tracy Vo's Today Show role is important to fellow Vietnamese-Australian Jody Phan], ''[[Huffington Post Australia]]''. Retrieved 20 January 2020.</ref>\n\nVo had previously been the local ''[[Today (Australian TV program)#News|Today Perth]]'' breakfast news presenter on [[STW9|Channel 9 in Perth]] in 2016 and 2017, presenting live half-hourly [[local news]] bulletins throughout the [[broadcast delay|time-delayed broadcast]] of the national ''Today'' program.<ref name=bio/>\n\nIn 2018, Vo was appointed as anchor of the Channel 9 Perth's local afternoon program, ''[[Nine News#local bulletins|Nine Live Perth]]''.<ref name=bio/>\n\nIn 2014, Vo published a book entitled ''Small Bamboo'', which detailed her parent's arrival in Australia in the late 1970's as [[Vietnamese boat people]] following the [[Vietnam War]].<ref>Vo, Tracy (2014), ''Small Bamboo: How my family's journey on a leaky boat led to our wonderful life in Australia'', [[Allen & Unwin]], {{ISBN| 9781743316153}}. Accessed 20 January 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.allenandunwin.com/browse/books/general-books/biography-autobiography/Small-Bamboo-Tracy-Vo-9781743316153 Biography & Autobiography: Small Bamboo], Allen & Unwin Book Publishers website. Retrieved 20 January 2020.</ref><ref name=heart/>\n\nVo grew up in the Perth suburb of Hammersley and attended Our Lady of Lourdes Catholic Primary School at [[Nollamara]] and then [[Hollywood Senior High School]] in [[Shenton Park]].<ref name=heart/>  Vo completed a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree at [[Curtin University]].<ref name=bio/>\n\nVo's early career included stints at Sydney radio station [[2SM]], and [[Sky News Australia]].<ref name=bio/><ref name=heart/>  She joined [[TCN|Channel 9 in Sydney]] in 2007 where she remained until 2012 when she returned to Perth for personal reasons, and commenced working as a journalist at [[STW|Channel 9 in Perth]].<ref>(26 August 2012) [https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/tracy-vo-heads-back-home-to-perth-to-care-for-her-parents/news-story/90258d70e25a4fba65add040fcce8b63 Tracy Vo heads back to Perth to care for parents], ''[[The Sunday Telegraph (Sydney)|The Sunday Telegraph]]''. Retrieved 20 January 2020.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box\n| title = ''[[Today (Australian TV program)|Today]]''<br />News presenter\n| before = Tom Steinfort\n| after = [[Alex Cullen]]\n| years = January 2020 \u2013 March 2020\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = ''[[Nine News|Nine Live Perth]]''<br />Presenter\n| before = [[Davina Smith]]\n| after = Louise Momber and Michael Genovese\n| years = 2018 \u2013 2019\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{TodayPresenters}}\n{{NineNewsAnchors}}\n\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vo, Tracy}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women television presenters]]\n[[Category:Nine News presenters]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Vietnamese descent]]\n[[Category:Australian women journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian women writers]]\n[[Category:Australian television presenters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian journalist, television presenter and author}}\n'''Tracy Vo''' (born 1983) is an Australian journalist, television presenter and author.<ref name=bio>[https://www.huffingtonpost.com.au/entry/tracy-vo-today-show-jody-phan_au_5dfacfe1e4b01834791aed62 Meet the Team: Tracy Vo], ''[[Nine News]]'' website. Accessed 20 January 2020.</ref><ref name=heart>Caccetta, Wendy (28 April 2014) [https://www.perthnow.com.au/news/wa/two-worlds-one-heart-tv-journalist-tracy-vo-highlights-her-struggles-in-book-small-bamboo-ng-59a8370cd0db3beea52283730943f5ae Two worlds, one heart: TV journalist Tracy Vo highlights her struggles in book Small Bamboo], ''[[The Sunday Times (Western Australia)|Perth Now]]''. Retrieved 20 January 2020.</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nVo is best known for her work with the [[Nine Network]], where she has been a ''[[Nine News]]'' reporter since 2007.<ref name=bio/>\n\nIn 2019, it was announced Vo had been appointed as the news presenter on the network's national breakfast show, ''[[Today (Australian TV program)|Today]]''.<ref>Prestipino, David; Moran, Robert (18 December 2020) [https://www.smh.com.au/culture/tv-and-radio/vo-and-co-to-give-new-today-show-a-westside-vibe-in-2020-20191218-p53l6x.html Vo and Co to give Today a \"westside vibe\" in 2020], ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]''. Retrieved 20 January 2020.</ref> She commenced this role on 6 January 2020.<ref>(7 January 2020) [https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/morning-shows/karl-stefanovics-big-comeback-pays-off-for-today/news-story/ec04c63c8bbab890c09eea256bb436ec Karl Stefanovic's big comeback pays off for Today], ''[[news.com.au]]''. Retrieved 20 January 2020.</ref> In March 2020, Vo permanently returned to Perth due to COVID-19 and to look after her parents<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/morning-shows/today-newsreader-tracy-vo-quits-role-to-move-back-to-perth/news-story/dc637b2cadd1fa0562ccfc5c4f14b083|title=Today show suffers another blow|date=2020-04-12|website=NewsComAu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>. Alex Cullen is currently presenting both news and sport. \n\nAs a [[Vietnamese-Australian]], Vo's appointment meant she became one of only a few Asian faces on [[Television in Australia|commercial television in Australia]].<ref>Cheer, Louise (18 December 2019) [https://au.lifestyle.yahoo.com/tracy-vo-new-today-newsreader-win-asian-representation-041532519.html Why Tracy Vo's Today role means so much to me], ''[[Yahoo! Lifestyle]]''. Retrieved 20 January 2020.</ref>  Nine's decision to appoint Vo to such a prominent role at the network was met with praise, and was described by one media outlet as \"symbolic of progress towards greater media representation of [[Multiculturalism in Australia|Australia's multicultural population]]\".<ref>Vrajlal, Alicia (19 December 2019) [https://www.huffingtonpost.com.au/entry/tracy-vo-today-show-jody-phan_au_5dfacfe1e4b01834791aed62 Why Tracy Vo's Today Show role is important to fellow Vietnamese-Australian Jody Phan], ''[[Huffington Post Australia]]''. Retrieved 20 January 2020.</ref>\n\nVo had previously been the local ''[[Today (Australian TV program)#News|Today Perth]]'' breakfast news presenter on [[STW9|Channel 9 in Perth]] in 2016 and 2017, presenting live half-hourly [[local news]] bulletins throughout the [[broadcast delay|time-delayed broadcast]] of the national ''Today'' program.<ref name=bio/>\n\nIn 2018, Vo was appointed as anchor of the Channel 9 Perth's local afternoon program, ''[[Nine News#local bulletins|Nine Live Perth]]''.<ref name=bio/>\n\nIn 2014, Vo published a book entitled ''Small Bamboo'', which detailed her parent's arrival in Australia in the late 1970's as [[Vietnamese boat people]] following the [[Vietnam War]].<ref>Vo, Tracy (2014), ''Small Bamboo: How my family's journey on a leaky boat led to our wonderful life in Australia'', [[Allen & Unwin]], {{ISBN| 9781743316153}}. Accessed 20 January 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.allenandunwin.com/browse/books/general-books/biography-autobiography/Small-Bamboo-Tracy-Vo-9781743316153 Biography & Autobiography: Small Bamboo], Allen & Unwin Book Publishers website. Retrieved 20 January 2020.</ref><ref name=heart/>\n\nVo grew up in the Perth suburb of Hammersley and attended Our Lady of Lourdes Catholic Primary School at [[Nollamara]] and then [[Hollywood Senior High School]] in [[Shenton Park]].<ref name=heart/>  Vo completed a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree at [[Curtin University]].<ref name=bio/>\n\nVo's early career included stints at Sydney radio station [[2SM]], and [[Sky News Australia]].<ref name=bio/><ref name=heart/>  She joined [[TCN|Channel 9 in Sydney]] in 2007 where she remained until 2012 when she returned to Perth for personal reasons, and commenced working as a journalist at [[STW|Channel 9 in Perth]].<ref>(26 August 2012) [https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/tracy-vo-heads-back-home-to-perth-to-care-for-her-parents/news-story/90258d70e25a4fba65add040fcce8b63 Tracy Vo heads back to Perth to care for parents], ''[[The Sunday Telegraph (Sydney)|The Sunday Telegraph]]''. Retrieved 20 January 2020.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box\n| title = ''[[Today (Australian TV program)|Today]]''<br />News presenter\n| before = Tom Steinfort\n| after = [[Alex Cullen]]\n| years = January 2020 \u2013 March 2020\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = ''[[Nine News|Nine Live Perth]]''<br />Presenter\n| before = [[Davina Smith]]\n| after = Louise Momber and Michael Genovese\n| years = 2018 \u2013 2019\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{TodayPresenters}}\n{{NineNewsAnchors}}\n\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vo, Tracy}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women television presenters]]\n[[Category:Nine News presenters]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Vietnamese descent]]\n[[Cate